( agence france - presse , tokyo , 15 th ) - a japanese court today rejected a compensation lawsuit of 132 - million yen ( 11.1 - million us dollars ) , which was put forward by six chinese people , who were forced to be a slave in a nickel mine in japan during world war ii .
the tokyo district court judge nannan said that although the government and the japanese metallurgical industry jointly committed illegal acts in 1944 , he rejected the lawsuit in 20 years in accordance with the civil law 's request for compensation .
nannan said : " the defendant 's responsibility has been terminated . "
five former chinese slaves , including liu zongroot , aged 72 , and a slave of a slave , sought wages , compensation , and apology from the japanese government and the japanese metallurgical industry corporation .
these six people were once a slave worker in the japanese metallurgical industry . during this period , they were frequently beaten , and they had no food or clothing .
the japanese metallurgical industry argued that the company was unable to confront the state 's implementation policy , while the japanese government said that according to the constitution at that time , it did not need to pay compensation to the plaintiff .
after the court announcement , liu zongen said at a press conference : " this is a lack of humanitarian judgment . "
he said they would appeal .
liu zongkan said , " i have the support of many japanese friends and i will fight to the end . "
the lawyer pointed out that the verdict " violated the historical record " and demanded that the japanese government and the japanese metallurgical industry pay compensation and apologize for the settlement of the issue .
the kyodo news agency reported that this was the first time that such a resistance was rejected in the litigation .
in 1944 , the japanese army arrested about 200 chinese , and then sent them to the dajiang nickel mining area in beijing , where they were a slave .
